🎯 Project Overview
Effective storage management ensures that data is organized and that applications never run out of disk space.
In this task, I practiced creating mount points, mounting storage devices, and monitoring disk health.

---

🛠️ Step-by-Step Implementation

1. Creating the Mount Point
A mount point is simply a directory where a storage device "plugs into" the Linux file system.
Bash
sudo mkdir -p /mnt/devops_data

2. Mounting a Volume
In a production environment, this would be an external SSD or a Cloud Volume (EBS). 
For practice, you can mount an existing partition or a loop device.
Bash
Example: Mounting a specific partition
sudo mount /dev/sdb1 /mnt/devops_data

3. Verifying the Mount
It is essential to confirm the system recognizes the new storage.
Bash
df -h        Purpose: Displays disk space usage in human-readable format (GB/MB).
Bash
mount | grep devops_data       Purpose: Confirms that the specific directory is correctly mapped to a device.


🧠 Key Commands Learned
df -h: Check how much space is left on all mounted filesystems.
du -sh: Check the size of a specific directory.
mount: Connect a physical device to the file tree.
umount: Safely disconnect a device.

